Architecture plan

Scope
- Issues #3-#12 turn the existing Next.js App Router TypeScript scaffold into a statically exported marketing site for "Agent Team for Founders".
- The site should stay frontend-only for this batch: static routes, public environment variables for configurable links, reusable UI primitives, and section components composed on the home page.

Module structure and file organization
- Keep the repository root as the Next.js application root.
- App shell:
  - `app/layout.tsx` owns `html`/`body`, metadata, font loading, and shared header/footer composition once those components exist.
  - `app/page.tsx` composes page sections in order: hero, value proposition, and future sections.
  - `app/globals.css` contains Tailwind directives, CSS custom properties, reset/base styles, and global element defaults.
- Shared components:
  - `components/layout/header.tsx` for sticky desktop/mobile navigation.
  - `components/layout/footer.tsx` for brand, copyright, and basic links.
  - `components/sections/hero.tsx` and `components/sections/value-proposition.tsx` for homepage content blocks.
  - `components/ui/button.tsx`, `components/ui/section.tsx`, `components/ui/card.tsx`, and `components/ui/icon.tsx` for primitives reused by layout and sections.
- Configuration and support files:
  - `tailwind.config.ts` and `postcss.config.mjs` for Tailwind.
  - `prettier.config.mjs` and ESLint config at the root for formatting/linting conventions.
  - `.env.example` documents public environment variables such as `NEXT_PUBLIC_CTA_URL`.
  - `lib/env.ts` can centralize safe reads of public env values and default fallbacks.
  - `lib/navigation.ts` can hold shared anchor IDs/labels used by header, footer, and sections.
- Shared types should be colocated when narrow. Promote to `types/` only if multiple unrelated modules need the same contract.

Dependencies between issues
- #3 is the foundation for styling and code quality; #6 and all UI work depend on Tailwind being wired.
- #4 depends on the scaffold and should configure `output: "export"` plus scripts before deployment-sensitive UI work accumulates.
- #5 depends on the scaffold and should land before hero/header CTAs need a configurable target.
- #6 depends on #3 and defines the visual contract consumed by #7-#12.
- #7 depends on #3/#6 and establishes the root shell that #8 and #9 plug into.
- #8 and #9 depend on #7 plus UI primitives from #10 where practical. If #10 lands later, keep their first implementation small and refactor onto primitives during #10.
- #10 depends on #6 because primitives should encode design tokens rather than hard-coded one-off styles.
- #11 depends on #5, #6, #7, and preferably #10 for CTA/button and section composition.
- #12 depends on #6 and #10, and should reuse the shared section/card patterns.

Key design decisions
- Use static export from Next.js; avoid server-only APIs, dynamic route behavior that cannot export, and runtime secrets.
- Use Tailwind for component styling with design tokens expressed in the Tailwind theme and mirrored as CSS variables where global styles need them.
- Keep the palette restrained and professional for a founder-focused software service; prioritize readable contrast, strong spacing rhythm, and responsive density over decorative effects.
- Treat navigation items and CTA URLs as shared data so header, footer, hero, and sections do not drift.
- Use small, typed React components with simple props; avoid introducing state libraries or animation libraries for these initial sections.
- Preserve the App Router conventions and keep the home page composition explicit so later issues can add sections without changing routing architecture.
